{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5772736c-2350-463e-8039-e668e4b29a2e","content":"For a NativeAOT .NET 11 app, you need the `createdump` path explicitly set (since NativeAOT doesn't bundle it), plus `SYS_PTRACE` for `createdump` to attach to the crashing process. Here's the pod spec:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nmetadata:\n  name: my-app\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: app\n      image: my-app:latest\n      env:\n        # Enable automatic crash dump generation\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n          value: \"1\"\n        # 4 = Full dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage)\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n          value: \"4\"\n        # Dump output path (%d=PID on some versions, %p=PID)\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n          value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p\"\n        # Point to your createdump install (required for NativeAOT)\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n          value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add:\n            # Required: createdump uses ptrace to read process memory\n            - SYS_PTRACE\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** — critical for NativeAOT since the runtime doesn't ship `createdump` inline; it must be told where to find it.\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** — `createdump` uses `ptrace()` to snapshot the process; without this capability the dump will silently fail.\n- **`emptyDir` volume** — keeps dumps off the container's overlay filesystem. Set `sizeLimit` appropriately for your app's memory footprint.\n\nTo **retrieve dumps** before the pod is evicted, you can either sidecar-sync them to blob storage or use `kubectl cp`:\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp my-app:/tmp/dumps ./local-dumps\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9efa5315-9bc3-4eeb-a1c1-6c8cedbb88cc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. The user is asking for guidance on configuring automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app in Kubernetes. Let me search for any relevant plugins or documentation in the repository.\n\nWait, there's no repository here - the directory is empty. The user is asking me to provide them with the configuration they need. Let me think about this from my knowledge of .NET diagnostics and Kubernetes.\n\nFor NativeAOT .NET apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps:\n\n1. **NativeAOT crash dumps**: NativeAOT apps don't have the same managed debugging infrastructure. The `createdump` tool can be used, but the environment variables for configuring it differ.\n\n\n2. The main environment variables I need to configure are `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` to turn on automatic dump generation, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to specify the dump format (ranging from mini to full), and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` to set where the dumps get written. There's also `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` for additional diagnostics output, and the older `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump` variant for compatibility.\n\nNow, NativeAOT complicates things since it doesn't rely on the CoreCLR runtime. Starting with .NET 8, NativeAOT does support crash dumps through `createdump`, and the same environment variables apply, but the behavior differs — the runtime won't automatically trigger `createdump` on a crash the way the managed runtime does. ativeAOT, I need to configure several environment variables: enable mini dumps with `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1`, specify the dump type and output path, and point to the `createdump` tool location since it won't be in the default path. For Kubernetes, I'll need an `emptyDir` volume for storage, the environment variables set on the container, the `SYS_PTRACE` capability so `createdump` can use ptrace, and core dump limits configured through ulimit or security context.\n\nRather than relying on node-level `/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern` settings, the `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` approach is cleaner since it works at the application level—when a crash happens, the NativeAOT runtime will invoke `createdump` directly. I'll put together the complete pod spec with the environment variables, volume mounts, security context, and resource considerations.\n\nWriting the Kubernetes YAML...","outputTokens":1715,"requestId":"7645:214D4D:1A643CF:1DF397B:69FE9277"},"id":"6d4fa1ea-fd33-4d30-bb55-0379820f8a85","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:49:13.118Z","parentId":"ee8d8be1-80f1-4954-b7b7-124db9cea93b"}
